# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Cannot force-kill threads |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** | Catch block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire *between any two IL instructions*, interrupting locks, `finally` blocks, and static constructors. .NET 8 requires cooperative cancellation instead.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<WorkItem> _channel;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts;
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public BackgroundProcessor()
    {
        _channel = Channel.CreateBounded<WorkItem>(capacity: 100);
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    }

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        {
            try
            {
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work then exit
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        // 1. Signal no more items will be written
        _channel.Writer.TryComplete();

        if (_workerTask is null) return;

        // 2. Give the worker time to drain gracefully
        var finished = await Task.WhenAny(
            _workerTask,
            Task.Delay(timeout.Value)
        );

        if (finished != _workerTask)
        {
            // 3. Cooperative cancellation — replaces Thread.Abort()
            await _cts.CancelAsync();

            try
            {
                await _workerTask;  // observe final result / exception
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Expected on cancellation
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Migration Decisions Explained

### 1. `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationToken` (cooperative cancellation)

```csharp
// ❌ .NET Framework — rips the thread out at an arbitrary point
_workerThread.Abort();

// ✅ .NET 8 — worker checks the token at safe points
await _cts.CancelAsync();
```

The worker *chooses* when to observe cancellation, so cleanup always runs correctly.

### 2. Blocking `GetNextItem()` → `Channel<T>` with async reads

```csharp
// ❌ .NET Framework — blocks the thread; only Thread.Abort() can unwedge it
var item = GetNextItem();

// ✅ .NET 8 — async read that responds to CancellationToken
await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
```

If `GetNextItem()` wraps an external blocking API you can't change, wrap it so cancellation still works:

```csharp
// Wrapping an unchangeable blocking call
var item = await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(), token);
```

> **Pitfall:** `Task.Run` with a token only prevents *starting* if already cancelled — it doesn't interrupt the blocking call. If `GetNextItem()` blocks forever, the task leaks. Prefer truly async APIs or poll-with-timeout loops.

### 3. `volatile bool` → `CancellationToken`

```csharp
// ❌ Polling a flag — easy to forget checks, no way to interrupt waits
while (_running) { ... }

// ✅ Token integrates with async/await, Channel, and most BCL APIs
await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
```

### 4. `Thread` → `Task.Run`

`Task.Run` uses the thread pool, avoids manual thread lifecycle management, and returns a `Task` you can `await` for clean shutdown.

### 5. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → structured timeout

```csharp
// ❌ Blocks the calling thread unconditionally
Thread.Sleep(2000);
if (_workerThread.IsAlive) _workerThread.Abort();

// ✅ Races the worker against a deadline, then cancels cooperatively
var finished = await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value));
if (finished != _workerTask) await _cts.CancelAsync();
```

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Catching `ThreadAbortException`** | Never thrown in .NET 8. If you port this catch block unchanged, it silently becomes dead code and your rollback logic never fires. |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | If you don't store and await the `Task`, unobserved exceptions vanish silently. Always assign to a field and `await` on shutdown. |
| **`CancellationToken` not threaded through** | If `ProcessItemAsync` calls sub-methods that ignore the token, cancellation won't propagate — the worker hangs despite `CancelAsync()`. Pass the token all the way down. |
| **Blocking calls inside async** | If `GetNextItem()` is truly synchronous and can block indefinitely, no `CancellationToken` will interrupt it. Refactor to async or use a poll-with-timeout pattern. |
| **Double-dispose of `CancellationTokenSource`** | If `StopAsync` and `DisposeAsync` can race, guard with a flag or use `Interlocked`. |
